Question1

Step 0 - 
cd ~
mkdir Linux-Lab-Assignment
cd Linux-Lab-Assignment
mkdir Question1
cd Question1

Explanation - 
cd ~ moves to the home directory
mkdir Linux-Lab-Assignment creates the main lab folder
mkdir Question1 creates the folder for Question 1

Step 1 - 
Create Documentation Files for Question 1
Code - 
touch commands.txt output.txt explanation.txt
This Creates files to store commands, outputs, and explanations

Part 1 - Display your currently logged-in username and all groups your user account belongs to.
Commands - 
whoami
groups

Output - 
coder sudo
Explanation - 
The whoami command displays the currently logged-in username.
The groups command shows all groups associated with the user account.

Part 2 - Display the current working directory and list all files and directories in that location using long format listing.
Commands - 
pwd
ls -l

Explanation - 
pwd displays the present working directory.
ls -l lists files and directories with permissions, ownership, and size details.

Part 3 - 
Commands -
echo "Linux user environment verified" > user_info.txt

Output - 
No output 
Explanation - 
This command creates the file user_info.txt and writes the verification message into it.

Part 4 - 
Commands - 
wc -c user_info.txt

Output -
32 user_info.txt

Explanation -
wc -c counts and displays the total number of characters present in the file.

Part 5 - 
Commands - 
man mkdir

Output - 
no entry for mkdir
See 'man 7 undocumented' for help when manual pages are not available

Explanation -
The man mkdir command was executed to view the manual page.
The system returned a message indicating that the manual page is not available on this system.
One useful option of mkdir is -p, which creates parent directories automatically if they do not exist.

Part 6 - 
Commands - 
ls ~ | sort

Output - 
Coursera 
data 
Desktop 
etc are the outputs. 

Explanation -
This command lists all files and directories in the home directory in alphabetical order.

Part 7 - 
Commands - 
echo "admin logged in" > log.txt
echo "user logged out" >> log.txt
grep "admin" log.txt 

Explanation -
grep searches for the word "admin" in log.txt and displays only the matching lines.

Part 8 - 
Commands - 
uname -r

Output - 
6.5.0-1024-aws
Explanation -
uname -r displays the version of the Linux kernel currently running.

Part 9 - 
Commands - 
ping -c 4 www.google.com

Output - 
PING www.google.com (142.251.111.103) 56(84) bytes of data. 
etc. 
Explanation -
This command sends ICMP packets to Google to verify network connectivity.

Part 10 - 
Commands - 
uptime

Output - 
06:03:49 up 10 days, 5:00, 0 users, load average: 2.29, 2.59, 2.67
Explanation -
The uptime command shows how long the system has been running, number of logged-in users, and load average.



